goals.question: What is the most common color in the dataset?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of colors in the dataset. If one color dominates the chart, it may indicate a bias in the data collection process.

goals.question: What is the relationship between saturation and color?

goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there are any differences in saturation levels across different colors. If there are significant differences, it may indicate that certain colors are more likely to have higher or lower saturation levels.

goals.question: What is the distribution of key values?

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.scatterplot(x='x', y='y', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the correlation between x and y?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='lumosity', color='blue')
    plt.axvline(data['lumosity'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Mean: {data['lumosity'].mean():.2f}")
    plt.axvline(data['lumosity'].median(), color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Median: {data['lumosity'].median():.2f}")
    plt.legend()
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('What is the distribution of lumosity?', wrap=True)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.dropna(subset=['color'])
    color_counts = data['color'].value_counts()
    color_counts = color_counts.reset_index()
    color_counts.columns = ['color', 'count']
    sns.barplot(x='color', y='count', data=color_counts)
    plt.title('What is the most common color in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Color')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.set(style="whitegrid")
    ax = sns.boxplot(x="color", y="saturation", data=data, palette="Set3")
    plt.title('What is the relationship between saturation and color?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Color')
    plt.ylabel('Saturation')
    plt.show()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.kdeplot(data=data, x='key', fill=True, color='blue', alpha=.5)
    plt.axvline(data['key'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f'Median: {data["key"].median():.2f}')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of key values?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
